<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF209-519-803  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 519 803.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Jan 13 1989 n1099* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC joins the crowd taking Apollo's Network Computing Systemseriously.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (licenses)Apple Computer Inc. (licenses).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; DEC.andO;Product:   Network Computing System (Computer program) (licenses).andO;Topic:     Network SoftwareDistributed ProcessingMultivendor Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DEC JOINS THE CROWD TAKING APOLLO'sandM;NETWORK COMPUTING SYSTEM SERIOUSLYandM;Apollo Computer Inc was celebrating a further endorsement of its NetworkComputing System distributed computing software this month with theannouncement that DEC had taken a licence to the software for evaluation andpossible inclusion within future products (CI No 1,086).andP;  In recent months,IBM and Hewlett- Packard Co have also licensed the software, which enablesusers to distribute parts of a single application program across amulti-vendor network to the computer most suited to the task.andP;  And accordingto Apollo spokesman Jim Barbagello, there will be a fourth announcement &quot;inthe next few weeks&quot;.andP;  Introduced in 1987, the Network Computing System hasnow been implemented by over 100 users, according to Apollo, and now supportsUnix-based hardware from Alliant Computer, Convex Computer, Cray Research,DEC, Hewlett-Packard Co, IBM, Multiflow Computers Inc, Prime Computer,Stratus Computer and Sun Microsystems.andP;  Barbagello said that the networkingsystem would enable DEC VAX hardware to be used as the host system for amulti-vendor networked computing solution.andP;  Sun has recently unbundled theOpen Network Computing component of its Network File System as a directcompetitor to the Apollo product, but does not include a &quot;location broker&quot;for automatic compute distribution, or automatic data translation betweenmachines.andO;</TEXT></DOC>